We recommended and management agreed that the MGL, through the MGSO and the MAO, in view of the gaps observed and raised in audit, to consider the:
a. conduct of periodic Physical Count of PPE items by directing concerned offices to perform the . comprehensive inventory taking of items under their responsibility, and the preparation of the RPCPPE by the Inventory Committee following the inventory taking;
d. proper tagging of PPE items by requiring the MGSO to manage the use of Property Stickers, and to maintain PCs, for each asset category indicating relevant information pertaining to particular PPE;
e. organization and safe keeping of TCTs, Deeds of Donation and Real Property Tax declaration of the MGL’s land properties. Ensure that original copies of these documents are safely kept and secured in the Municipal Treasurer’s Office’s (MTO) vault, and that second copies are to be made available in the MGSO’s office. Also, for accounting purposes, to provide the same set of documents to the MAO, for the eventual recording of corresponding land items in the MGL’s books;
f. immediate identification of PPE items not included in the depreciation schedule to determine if these items are no longer serviceable and so corresponding values may be dropped from the books. Otherwise, compute for the accumulated depreciation to reflect accurate carrying values;
g. gathering of necessary data/information concerning the disposed of unserviceable PPEs to serve as bases in dropping the PPE items in the books of accounts and to process the gain/loss computation on the sale of the subject property; and
h. drawing of necessary adjusting journal entries to adjust the income recognized arising from the disposal of PPE items that eventually caused the overstatement of the Government Equity balance.

We recommend and the management agreed to:
b. Determine the road lots covered by TCTs, Deeds of Donation, and Usufruct Agreements, and retrieve the appropriate documents relative thereto. Ensure that original copies of these documents are safely kept and secured in the MTO’s vault, and that second copies are to be made available in the General Services Office. Also, for accounting purposes, to provide the same set of documents to the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) for the eventual recording of corresponding road lots in the MGL’s books;
c. updating of the local road map, and ascertain those that are under public domain. Road lots classified under, and/or are previously on public domain, necessitate proper disclosures in the Notes to the Financial Statements; and
g. Determination of the undertakings pertaining to rehabilitation and/or re-blocking, and on which road network do they belong, for identification and derecognition purposes;

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Take the necessary steps in conducting the Municipal Market wide assessment in order to be appraised of the actual condition of the same vis-à-vis the intendments of the local revenue code;
b. Prepare a comprehensive status report as regards the Municipal Market, to include but not limited to the names of actual occupants vis-à-vis names as registered in the corresponding business permits; actual businesses undertaken, either by the actual occupants or the stall rights holder versus the ones actually applied for by the latter in the respective business permits, etc.;
c. Develop and/or craft the corresponding Implementing Rules and Regulations, in the form of Operations Manual for the Municipal Public Market, taking into account the streamlining and definition of processes and procedures;
d. Revisit the provisions of the Local Revenue Code of the Municipality as regards the matters relative to the market operations vis-à-vis actual practices as regards the revenue recognition;
e. Review the records, documents, lease agreements, ledgers, if any, and ascertain the receivables, and draw necessary journal entries to have the same recorded in keeping with the accrual basis of accounting for revenues;
f. Draw separate financial information and reports as regards the operations of the LEEs, as if these were independent segments, in keeping with the standards on segment reporting; and
g. Draw an analysis of the operations of the LGU’s Local Economic Enterprises, in particular the Public Market Operations, and render a formal report relative to the same, with the emphasis on the viability and/or sustainability of the same.

