We recommended and Management agreed to improve the processes of planning, prioritization and budgeting of SEF through:
a. Instituting measures to make the LSB more proactive and effective in introducing educational reforms within its capacity;
b. The formulation of development programs on education for the Municipal Government, articulating the collective vision of the major stakeholders;
c. Increasing participation and involvement of various sectors, including but not limited to parents, teachers, non-teaching personnel, and among others, in the regular consultative meetings of the LSB; and
d. Strictly requiring the submission of the respective schools’ budget proposals together with their annual appropriations from the national government to be able to properly identify the items for funding augmentation;
e. Develop and implement measures to make the processes of disbursement more transparent by adhering as much as possible to the law, rules and regulations; and
f. Refrain from accommodating expenditures which do not fall within the recommended programs, activities and projects chargeable against the SEF.
g. Draw necessary adjusting journal entries to reclassify the previously recorded transactions in order to reflect the same in their correct account classifications; and
h. Enhance the LGU’s accounting control on the classification of accounts in order to prevent the recurrence of misclassifying accounts.
i. Enhance accountability of the acquired and issued assets and/or properties by conducting regular physical inventory of the same, and evaluating on a timely basis the status and issuance of these subject assets to monitor their whereabouts and serviceability; and
j. Revisit the relevant guidelines on SEF and related rules and regulations on property, supply and inventory management for the proper disposition and issuance of LGU procured assets;
k. Hasten the development of measures, within its capacity, and through the LSB and the Municipal Planning Development Office (MPDO), to assess projects, activities and programs with respect not only to the desired outputs, but as well to the outcomes and impacts these projects have to the locality.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
a. Fast track the revision of the SWMP based on the newly adopted standard and submit the same to NSWMC for review;
b. Regularly practice the earlier drafting, preparation and submission of the SWMP, with a view of the previously obtained feedbacks and/or comments from the concerned approving authority.
c. Adopt measures for the immediate closure of the open dump in compliance with the Law, Rules and Regulations;
d. Draft policies and/or guidelines on the wearing of protective gears and equipment for personnel during collection and disposal of wastes; and
e. Strengthen the measures to address the problem on burning of solid wastes in the dump site. Also, conduct information drive/campaign regarding the proper management of solid wastes; the effects and/or impacts it bring to the quality of life.

We recommended that the Management should: 

Exert all efforts for the collection of receivables;

Reconcile and analyze the accounts to determine whether they warrant adjustment or write-off in accordance with existing COA rules and regulations;

Furnish certification and/or reasons why the books of accounts/records/financial statements/schedules and supporting documents cannot be located; and

Require proper turn-over of documents/pending work from officials and employees retiring/separating from office/service to ensure completeness of records.

We have recommended that:

a.	The management should exert diligent and continuous efforts to have a full accounting and settlement of long outstanding cash advances by requiring all accountable officers concerned to refund, submit documents and/or make a proper accounting of their existing cash advances as well as stop the practice of granting additional cash advances unless the previous ones are first settled;

b.	The management should direct the Accounting personnel to review and analyze prior year’s records on cash   advances and prepare periodic reports, such as aging of accounts and other relevant reports for monitoring purposes. Any existing claim of accountable officers concerned against the municipality may be used to offset the cash advances;

c.	Establish a policy on monitoring of cash advances to ensure that immediate action is taken to prevent occurrence of unliquidated cash advances. A system should be in place that would prevent retiring or resigning employees with accountabilities from obtaining the required office clearance unless there is full settlement thereof.

We recommended that the:

Municipal Accountant make a necessary adjusting entry to reclassify the cost of the hanging bridge to its appropriate Infrastructure Asset account in order to correct the overstatement/understatement of the affected asset accounts in the financial statements;

We recommended that a JEV be drawn immediately upon submission of liquidation report to grantor agency, and transfer the cost of completed projects from the Trust Fund to the General Fund books.
